    "chapterRef": "Chapter 1 · The Ultraviolet Catastrophe",
    "title": "How classical physics predicted an impossible infinity",
    "excerpt": "Heat almost anything hot enough and it begins to glow. Two objects at the same temperature glow with the same color, whatever they are made of — a clean, universal fact any good theory ought to explain with ease. That is precisely where the trouble started: fed into the established physics of the day, the theory did not miss by a little, it predicted a catastrophe — infinite energy piling up toward the ultraviolet."
